s the true costs and hidden dangers of the project, as told to her by the local farmers, ranchers, and First Nations leaders who tried to stop the dam and the wholesale destruction of their valley in courts of law and the court of public opinion. This modern-day David-and-Goliath story, told in frank and moving prose, stands as a much-needed cautionary tale during an era when concerns about global warming have helped justify a renaissance of environmentally irresponsible hydro megaprojects around the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDamsxEnvironmental aspectszPeace River Valley (B.C. and Alta.). 0aFarmerszPeace River Valley (B.C. and Alta.). 0aProtest movementszPeace River Valley (B.C. and Alta.). 0aWater resources developmentxEnvironmental aspectszPeace River Valley (B.C. and Alta.). 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh1 aNeve, Alex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311141792940uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077489027440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774890274423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774890274/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-141792-9  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles